# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: arak-drink
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] Absinthe was created in the canton of Neuchâtel in Switzerland in the late 18th century by the French physician Pierre Ordinaire.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] It rose to great popularity as an alcoholic drink in late 19th- and early 20th-century France, particularly among Parisian artists and writers.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] The consumption of absinthe was opposed by social conservatives and prohibitionists, partly due to its association with bohemian culture.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] From Europe and the Americas, notable absinthe drinkers included Ernest Hemingway, James Joyce, Lewis Carroll, Charles Baudelaire, Paul Verlaine, Arthur Rimbaud, and Henri de Toulouse-Lautrec.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] Absinthe has often been portrayed as a dangerously addictive psychoactive drug and hallucinogen, which gave birth to the term *absinthism*.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] The chemical compound thujone, which is present in the spirit in trace amounts, was blamed for its alleged harmful effects.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] By 1915, absinthe had been banned in the United States and much of Europe, including France, the Netherlands, Belgium, Switzerland, and Austria-Hungary, though it has not been demonstrated to be any more dangerous than ordinary spirits.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] Recent studies have shown that absinthe's psychoactive properties, apart from those attributable to its alcohol content, have been exaggerated.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] Absinthe's revival began in the 1990s, following the adoption of modern European Union food and beverage laws that removed long-standing barriers to its production and sale.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] By the early 21st century, nearly 200 brands of absinthe were being produced in a dozen countries, most notably in France, Switzerland, Austria, Germany, the Netherlands, Spain, and the Czech Republic.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] The French word *absinthe* can refer either to the alcoholic beverage, or less commonly, to the actual wormwood plant.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] Absinthe is derived from the Latin *absinthium*, which in turn comes from the Greek ἀψίνθιον *apsínthion* 'wormwood'.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] Some argue that the word means "undrinkable" in Greek, but it may instead be linked to the Persian root, in Persian called *spand* or *aspand* or the variant *esfand*, which meant *Peganum harmala*, also called Syrian rue in English, although it is not a variety of rue, another famously bitter herb.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] That *Artemisia absinthium* was commonly burned as a protective offering may suggest that its origins lie in the reconstructed Proto-Indo-European language root **spend*, meaning "to perform a ritual" or "make an offering".
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] Whether the word was a borrowing from Persian into Greek, or from a common ancestor of both, is unclear.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] Alternatively, the Greek word may originate in a pre-Greek substrate word, marked by the non-Indo-European consonant complex -νθ *-nth*.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] Alternative spellings for absinthe include *absinth*, *absynthe*, and *absenta*.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] *Absinth* (without the final *e*) is a spelling variant most commonly applied to absinthes produced in central and eastern Europe, and is specifically associated with Bohemian-style absinthes.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] The precise origin of absinthe is unclear.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] The medical use of wormwood dates back to ancient Egypt and is mentioned in the Ebers Papyrus from around 1550 BC.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] Wormwood extracts and wine-soaked wormwood leaves were used as remedies by the ancient Greeks.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] Moreover, some evidence exists of a wormwood-flavoured wine in ancient Greece called *absinthites oinos*.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] Lucretius' *De Rerum Natura* (I, 936–950) says that a drink containing wormwood was given as medicine to children in a cup with honey on the brim to make it drinkable.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] The first evidence of absinthe, in the sense of a distilled spirit containing green anise and fennel, dates to the 18th century.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] According to popular legend, it began as an all-purpose patent remedy created by Dr.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] Pierre Ordinaire, a French doctor living in Couvet, Switzerland, around 1792 (the exact date varies by account).
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] Ordinaire's recipe was passed on to the Henriod sisters of Couvet, who sold it as a medicinal elixir.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] By other accounts, the Henriod sisters may have been making the elixir before Ordinaire's arrival.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] In either case, a certain Major Dubied acquired the formula from the sisters in 1797 and opened the first absinthe distillery named Dubied Père et Fils in Couvet with his son Marcellin and son-in-law Henry-Louis Pernod.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] In 1805, they built a second distillery in Pontarlier, France, under the company name Maison Pernod Fils.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] Pernod Fils remained one of the most popular brands of absinthe until the drink was banned in France in 1914.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] Absinthe's popularity grew steadily through the 1840s, when it was given to French troops in Algeria as a malaria preventive, and the troops brought home their taste for it.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] Absinthe became so popular in bars, bistros, cafés, and cabarets by the 1860s that the hour of 5 pm was called *l'heure verte* 'the green hour'.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] It was favoured by all social classes, from the wealthy bourgeoisie to poor artists and ordinary working-class people.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] By the 1880s, mass production had caused the price to drop sharply, and the French were drinking 36 million litres (9,500,000 US gal) per year by 1910.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] Absinthe was exported widely from France and Switzerland and attained some degree of popularity in other countries, including Spain, the United Kingdom, the United States, and the Czech Republic.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] It was never banned in Spain or Portugal, and its production and consumption have never ceased.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] It gained a temporary popularity spike during the early 20th century, corresponding with the Art Nouveau and Modernism aesthetic movements.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] New Orleans has a cultural association with absinthe and is credited as the birthplace of the Sazerac, perhaps the earliest absinthe cocktail.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] The Old Absinthe House bar on Bourbon Street began selling absinthe in the first half of the 19th century.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] Its Catalan lease-holder, Cayetano Ferrer, named it the Absinthe Room in 1874 due to the drink's popularity, which was served in the Parisian style.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] It was frequented by Mark Twain, Oscar Wilde, Franklin Delano Roosevelt, Aleister Crowley, and Frank Sinatra.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] Absinthe became associated with violent crimes and social disorder, and one modern writer claims that this trend was spurred by fabricated claims and smear campaigns, which he claims were orchestrated by the temperance movement and the wine industry.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] Edgar Degas's 1876 painting **The Absinthe Drinker** or **Glass of Absinthe** (**L'Absinthe**) can be seen at the Musée d'Orsay epitomising the popular view of absinthe addicts as sodden and benumbed, and Émile Zola described its effects in his novel *L'Assommoir*.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] In 1905, Swiss farmer Jean Lanfray murdered his wife and two children and then attempted to kill himself after drinking absinthe.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] Lanfray had drunk a lot of wine and brandy before the killings, but that was overlooked or ignored, and blame for the murders was placed solely on his consumption of two glasses of absinthe.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] The Lanfray murders were the tipping point in this hotly debated topic, and a subsequent petition collected more than 82,000 signatures to ban it in Switzerland.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] It was approved by voters, and the prohibition of absinthe was written into the Swiss constitution.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] In 1906, Belgium and Brazil banned the sale and distribution of absinthe although these were not the first countries to take such action.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] It had been banned as early as 1898 in the colony of the Congo Free State.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] The Netherlands banned it in 1909, Switzerland in 1910, the United States in 1912, and France in 1914.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] The prohibition of absinthe in France eventually led to the popularity of pastis, and to a lesser extent, ouzo, and other anise-flavoured spirits that do not contain wormwood.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] Following the conclusion of the First World War, production of the Pernod Fils brand was resumed at the Banus distillery in Catalonia, Spain (where absinthe was still legal), but gradually declining sales saw the cessation of production in the 1960s.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] In Switzerland, the ban served only to drive the production of absinthe underground.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] Clandestine home distillers produced colourless absinthe (*la Bleue*), which was easier to conceal from the authorities.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] Many countries never banned absinthe, notably the United Kingdom, where it had never been as popular as in continental Europe.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] British importer BBH Spirits began to import Hill's Absinth from the Czech Republic in the 1990s, as the UK had never formally banned it, and this sparked a modern resurgence in its popularity.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] It began to reappear during a revival in the 1990s in countries where it was never banned.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] Forms of absinthe available during that time consisted almost exclusively of Czech, Spanish, and Portuguese brands that were of recent origin, typically consisting of Bohemian-style products.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] Connoisseurs considered these of inferior quality and not representative of the 19th-century spirit.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] In 2000, La Fée Absinthe became the first commercial absinthe distilled and bottled in France since the 1914 ban, but it is now one of dozens of brands that are produced and sold within France.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] In the Netherlands, the restrictions were challenged by Amsterdam wine seller Menno Boorsma in July 2004, thus confirming the legality of absinthe once again.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] Similarly, Belgium lifted its long-standing ban on 1 January 2005 citing a conflict with the adopted food and beverage regulations of the single European Market.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] In Switzerland, the constitutional ban was repealed in 2000 during an overhaul of the national constitution although the prohibition was written into ordinary law instead.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] That law was later repealed, and absinthe was made legal on March 1, 2005.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] The drink was never officially banned in Spain although it began to fall out of favour in the 1940s and almost vanished into obscurity.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] Catalonia has seen a significant resurgence since 2007 when one producer established operations there.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] Absinthe has never been illegal to import or manufacture in Australia although importation requires a permit under the Customs (Prohibited Imports) Regulation 1956 due to a restriction on importing any product containing oil of wormwood.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] In 2000, an amendment made all wormwood species prohibited herbs for food purposes under Food Standard 1.4.4.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] Prohibited and Restricted Plants and Fungi.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] However, this amendment was found inconsistent with other parts of the pre-existing Food Code, and it was withdrawn in 2002 during the transition between the two codes, thereby continuing to allow absinthe manufacture and importation through the existing permit-based system.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] These events were erroneously reported by the media as it having been reclassified from a *prohibited* product to a *restricted* product.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] In 2007, the French brand Lucid became the first genuine absinthe to receive a Certificate of Label Approval for import into the United States since 1912, following independent efforts by representatives from Lucid and Kübler to overturn the long-standing U.S. ban.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] George Spirits of Alameda, California became the first brand of American-made absinthe produced in the United States since the ban.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] Since that time, other micro-distilleries have started producing small batches in the United States.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] The French Absinthe Ban of 1915 was repealed in May 2011 following petitions by the *Fédération Française des Spiritueux*, which represents French distillers, and the French Senate voted to repeal the prohibition in April 2011.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] In Switzerland, the village of Môtiers, Val-de-Travers, near Neuchâtel, became the focal point of production and promotion of the liquor after a ban of nearly 100 years was lifted.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] The national *Maison de l'Absinthe* (House of Absinthe), with its attached museum, is located in the former courthouse where absinthe distillers were formerly prosecuted.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] The 21st century has seen new types of absinthe, including various frozen preparations, that have become increasingly popular.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] Most countries have no legal definition for absinthe, whereas the method of production and content of spirits such as whisky, brandy, and gin are globally defined and regulated.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] Therefore, producers are at liberty to label a product as "absinthe" or "absinth" without regard to any specific legal definition or quality standards.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] Producers of legitimate absinthes employ one of two historically defined processes to create the finished spirit – distillation or cold mixing.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] In the sole country (Switzerland) that does possess a legal definition of absinthe, distillation is the only permitted method of production.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] Distilled absinthe employs a method of production similar to that of high-quality gin.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] Botanicals are initially macerated in distilled base alcohol before being redistilled to exclude bitter principles, and impart the desired complexity and texture to the spirit.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] The distillation of absinthe first yields a colourless distillate that leaves the alembic at around 72% ABV.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] The distillate may be reduced and bottled clear, to produce a *Blanche* or *la Bleue* absinthe, or it may be coloured to create a *verte* using natural or artificial colouring.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] Traditional absinthes obtain their green color strictly from the chlorophyll of whole herbs, which is extracted from the plants during the secondary maceration.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] This step involves steeping plants such as petite wormwood, hyssop, and melissa (among other herbs) in the distillate.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] Chlorophyll from these herbs is extracted, giving the drink its famous green color.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] This step also provides a herbal complexity that is typical of high-quality absinthe.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] The natural coloring process is critical for absinthe ageing since the chlorophyll remains chemically active.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] The chlorophyll serves a similar role in absinthe as tannins do in wine or brown liquors.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] After the coloring process, the resulting product is diluted with water to the desired alcohol percentage.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] The flavor of absinthe is said to improve materially with storage, and many distilleries, before the ban, aged their absinthe in settling tanks before bottling.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] Many modern absinthes are produced using a cold-mix process.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] This inexpensive method of production does not involve distillation, and is regarded as inferior for the same reasons that give cause for cheaply compounded gin to be legally differentiated from distilled gin.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] The cold mixing process involves the simple blending of flavouring essences and artificial colouring in commercial alcohol, in similar fashion to most flavoured vodkas and inexpensive liqueurs and cordials.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] Some modern cold-mixed absinthes have been bottled at strengths approaching 90% ABV.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] Others are presented simply as a bottle of plain alcohol with a small amount of powdered herbs suspended within it.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] The lack of a formal legal definition in most countries to regulate the production and quality of absinthe has enabled cheaply made products to be falsely presented as traditional in production and composition.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] In Switzerland, the only country with a formal legal definition of absinthe, any absinthe product not obtained by maceration and distillation or coloured artificially cannot be sold as absinthe.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] Absinthe is traditionally prepared from a distillation of neutral alcohol, various herbs, spices, and water.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] Traditional absinthes were redistilled from a white grape spirit (or *eau de vie*), while lesser absinthes were more commonly made from alcohol from grains, beets, or potatoes.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] The principal botanicals are grande wormwood, green anise, and florence fennel, which are often called "the holy trinity".
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] Many other herbs may be used as well, such as petite wormwood (*Artemisia pontica* or Roman wormwood), hyssop, melissa, star anise, angelica, peppermint, coriander, and veronica.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] One early recipe was included in 1864's *The English and Australian Cookery Book*.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] It directed the maker to "Take of the tops of wormwood, four pounds; root of angelica, calamus aromaticus, aniseed, leaves of dittany, of each one ounce; alcohol, four gallons.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] Macerate these substances during eight days, add a little water, and distil by a gentle fire, until two gallons are obtained.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] Adding to absinthe's negative reputation in the late 19th and early 20th centuries, unscrupulous makers of the drink omitted the traditional colouring phase of production in favour of adding toxic copper salts to artificially induce a green tint.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] This practice may be responsible for some of the alleged toxicity historically associated with this beverage.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] Many modern-day producers resort to other shortcuts, including the use of artificial food coloring to create the green color.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] Additionally, at least some cheap absinthes produced before the ban were reportedly adulterated with poisonous antimony trichloride, reputed to enhance the louching effect.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] Absinthe may also be naturally coloured pink or red using rose or hibiscus flowers.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] This was referred to as a *rose* (pink) or *rouge* (red) absinthe.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] Only one historical brand of rose absinthe has been documented.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] Absinthe was historically bottled at 45–74% ABV.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] Some modern Franco–Suisse absinthes are bottled at up to 83% ABV, while some modern, cold-mixed bohemian-style absinthes are bottled at up to 89.9% ABV.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] The modern-day interest in absinthe has spawned a rash of absinthe kits from sellers claiming they produce homemade absinthe.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] Kits often call for soaking herbs in vodka or alcohol or adding a liquid concentrate to vodka or alcohol to create an ersatz absinthe.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] Such practices usually yield a harsh substance that bears little resemblance to the genuine article and is considered inauthentic by any practical standard.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] Some concoctions may even be dangerous, especially if they call for a potentially poisonous inclusion of herbs, oils, or extracts.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] In at least one documented case, a person suffered acute kidney injury after drinking 10 ml of pure wormwood oil.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] In baking and in preparing the classic New Orleans-style Sazerac cocktail, anise-flavored liqueurs and pastis have often been used as a substitute if absinthe is unavailable.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] The traditional French preparation involves placing a sugar cube on top of a specially designed slotted spoon and placing the spoon on a glass filled with a measure of absinthe.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] Iced water is poured or dripped over the sugar cube to mix the water into the absinthe.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] The final preparation contains 1 part absinthe and 3–5 parts water.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] As water dilutes the spirit, those components with poor water solubility (mainly those from anise, fennel, and star anise) come out of solution and cloud the drink.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] The resulting milky opalescence is called the *louche* (/luʃ/, French: 'opaque' or 'shady').
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] The release of these dissolved essences coincides with a perfuming of herbal aromas and flavours that "blossom" or "bloom", and brings out subtleties that are otherwise muted within the neat spirit.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] This reflects what is perhaps the oldest and purest method of preparation, and is often referred to as the *French method*.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] The *Bohemian method* is a recent invention that involves fire, and was not performed during absinthe's peak of popularity in the Belle Époque.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] Like the French method, a sugar cube is placed on a slotted spoon over a glass containing one shot of absinthe.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] The sugar is soaked in alcohol (usually more absinthe), and then set ablaze.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] The flaming sugar cube is then dropped into the glass, thus igniting the absinthe.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] Finally, a shot glass of water is added to douse the flames.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] This method tends to produce a stronger drink than the French method.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] A variant of the Bohemian method involves allowing the fire to extinguish on its own.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] This variant is sometimes referred to as "cooking the absinthe" or "the flaming green fairy".
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] The origin of this burning ritual may borrow from a coffee and brandy drink that was served at Café Brûlot, in which a sugar cube soaked in brandy was set aflame.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] Most experienced absintheurs do not recommend the Bohemian Method and consider it a modern gimmick, as it can destroy the absinthe flavour and present a fire hazard due to the unusually high alcohol content present in absinthe.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] In 19th-century Parisian cafés, upon receiving an order for absinthe, a waiter would present the patron with a dose of absinthe in a suitable glass, sugar, absinthe spoon, and a carafe of iced water.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] It was up to the patron to prepare the drink, as the inclusion or omission of sugar was strictly an individual preference, as was the amount of water used.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] As the popularity of the drink increased, additional accoutrements of preparation appeared, including the absinthe fountain, which was effectively a large jar of iced water with spigots, mounted on a lamp base.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] This lets drinkers prepare several drinks at once – and with a hands-free drip, patrons could socialise while louching a glass.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] Although many bars served absinthe in standard glassware, several glasses were specifically designed for the French absinthe preparation ritual.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] Absinthe glasses were typically fashioned with a dose line, bulge, or bubble in the lower portion denoting how much absinthe should be poured.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] One "dose" of absinthe ranged anywhere around 2–2.5 fluid ounces (60–75 ml).
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] In addition to being prepared with sugar and water, absinthe emerged as a popular cocktail ingredient in both the United Kingdom and the United States.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] By 1930, dozens of fancy cocktails that called for absinthe had been published in numerous credible bartender guides.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] One of the most famous of these libations is Ernest Hemingway's "Death in the Afternoon" cocktail, a tongue-in-cheek concoction that contributed to a 1935 collection of celebrity recipes.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] The directions are: "Pour one jigger absinthe into a Champagne glass.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] Add iced Champagne until it attains the proper opalescent milkiness.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] Most categorical alcoholic beverages have regulations governing their classification and labelling, while those governing absinthe have always been conspicuously lacking.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] According to popular treatises from the 19th century, absinthe could be loosely categorised into several grades (*ordinaire*, *demi-fine*, *fine*, and *Suisse* – the latter does not denote origin), in order of increasing alcoholic strength and quality.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] Many contemporary absinthe critics simply classify absinthe as *distilled* or *mixed*, according to its production method.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] And while the former is generally considered far superior in quality to the latter, an absinthe's simple claim of being 'distilled' makes no guarantee as to the quality of its base ingredients or the skill of its maker.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] Absinthe that is artificially coloured or clear is aesthetically stable and can be bottled in clear glass.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] If naturally colored absinthe is exposed to light or air for a prolonged period, the chlorophyll gradually becomes oxidized, which has the effect of gradually changing the color from green to yellow green, and eventually to brown.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] The colour of absinthe that has completed this transition was historically referred to as *feuille morte* ("dead leaf").
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] In the pre-ban era, this natural phenomenon was favourably viewed, for it confirmed the product in question was coloured naturally, and not artificially with potentially toxic chemicals.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] Predictably, vintage absinthes often emerge from sealed bottles as distinctly amber in tint due to decades of slow oxidation.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] Though this colour change presents no adverse impact to the flavour of absinthe, it is generally desired to preserve the original colour, which requires that naturally coloured absinthe be bottled in dark, light-resistant bottles.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] Absinthe intended for decades of storage should be kept in a cool (room temperature), dry place, away from light and heat.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] Absinthe should not be stored in the refrigerator or freezer, as the anethole may polymerise inside the bottle, creating an irreversible precipitate, and adversely impacting the original flavour.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] Absinthe has been frequently described in modern times as being hallucinogenic, a claim refuted by modern science.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] The belief that absinthe induces hallucinogenic effects is rooted, at least partly, in the findings of 19th-century French psychiatrist Valentin Magnan, who carried out ten years of experiments with wormwood oil.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] In the course of this research, he studied 250 cases of alcoholism and concluded that those who abused absinthe were worse off than those who abused other alcoholic drinks, experiencing rapid-onset hallucinations.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] Such accounts by opponents of absinthe (like Magnan) were cheerfully embraced by famous absinthe drinkers, many of whom were bohemian artists or writers.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] Two famous artists who helped popularise the notion that absinthe had powerful psychoactive properties were Toulouse-Lautrec and Vincent van Gogh.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] In one of the best-known written accounts of absinthe drinking, an inebriated Oscar Wilde described a phantom sensation of having tulips brush against his legs after leaving a bar at closing time.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] Notions of absinthe's alleged hallucinogenic properties were again fuelled in the 1970s when a scientific paper suggested that thujone's structural similarity to tetrahydrocannabinol (THC), the active chemical in cannabis, presented the possibility of THC receptor affinity.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] Counterevidence to this was published in 1999.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] The debate over whether absinthe produces effects on the human mind in addition to those of alcohol has not been resolved conclusively.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] The effects of absinthe have been described by some as mind-opening.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] The most commonly reported experience is a "clear-headed" feeling of inebriation – a form of "lucid drunkenness".
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] Chemist, historian, and absinthe distiller Ted Breaux has claimed that the alleged secondary effects of absinthe may be because some of the herbal compounds in the drink act as stimulants, while others act as sedatives, creating an overall lucid effect of awakening.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] The long-term effects of moderate absinthe consumption in humans remain unknown, although herbs traditionally used to produce absinthe are reported to have both painkilling and antiparasitic properties.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] Today it is known that absinthe does not cause hallucinations.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] It was once widely promoted that excessive absinthe drinking caused effects that were discernible from those associated with alcoholism, a belief that led to the coining of the term *absinthism*.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] One of the first vilifications of absinthe followed an 1864 experiment in which Magnan simultaneously exposed one guinea pig to large doses of pure wormwood vapour, and another to alcohol vapours.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] The guinea pig exposed to wormwood vapour experienced convulsive seizures, while the animal exposed to alcohol did not.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] Magnan would later blame the naturally occurring (in wormwood) chemical thujone for these effects.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] Thujone, once widely believed to be an active chemical in absinthe, is a GABA antagonist, and while it can produce muscle spasms in large doses, there is no direct evidence to suggest it causes hallucinations.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] Past reports estimated thujone concentrations in absinthe as being up to 260 mg/kg.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] As such, most traditionally crafted absinthes, both vintage and modern, fall within the current EU standards.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] Tests conducted on mice to study toxicity showed an oral LD50 of about 45 mg thujone per kg of body weight, which represents far more absinthe than could be realistically consumed.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] The high percentage of alcohol in absinthe would result in mortality long before thujone could become a factor.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] In documented cases of acute thujone poisoning as a result of oral ingestion, the source of thujone was not commercial absinthe, but rather non-absinthe-related sources, such as common essential oils (which may contain as much as 50% thujone).
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] One study published in the *Journal of Studies on Alcohol* concluded that high doses (0.28 mg/kg) of thujone in alcohol had negative effects on attention performance in a clinical setting.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] It delayed reaction time, and caused subjects to concentrate their attention on the central field of vision.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] Low doses (0.028 mg/kg) did not produce an effect noticeably different from the plain alcohol control.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] While the effects of the high dose samples were statistically significant in a double blind test, the test subjects themselves were unable to reliably identify which samples contained thujone.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] For the average 65 kg (143 lb) man, the high dose samples in the study would equate to 18.2 mg of thujone.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] The EU limit of 35 mg/L of thujone in absinthe means that given the highest permitted thujone content, that individual would need to consume approximately 0.5 litres of high-proof (e.g.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] 50%+ ABV) spirit before the thujone could be metabolized to display effects detectable in a clinical setting, which would result in a potentially lethal BAC of >0.4%.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] Most countries (except Switzerland) at present do not possess a legal definition of absinthe (unlike Scotch whisky or cognac).
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] Accordingly, producers are free to label a product "absinthe" or "absinth", whether or not it bears any resemblance to the traditional spirit.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] Absinthe is readily available in many bottle shops.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] Bitters may contain a maximum 35 mg/kg thujone, while other alcoholic beverages can contain a maximum 10 mg/kg.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] The domestic production and sale of absinthe is regulated by state licensing laws.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] These controls have now been repealed, and permission is no longer required.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] Absinthe was prohibited in Brazil until 1999 and was brought by entrepreneur Lalo Zanini and legalised in the same year.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] Presently, absinthe sold in Brazil must abide by the national law that restricts all spirits to a maximum of 54% ABV.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] While this regulation is enforced throughout channels of legal distribution, it may be possible to find absinthe containing alcohol in excess of the legal limit in some restaurants or food fairs.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] In Canada, liquor laws concerning the production, distribution, and sale of spirits are written and enforced by individual provincial government monopolies.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] Each product is subject to the approval of a respective individual provincial liquor board before it can be sold in that province.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] Importation is a federal matter and is enforced by the Canada Border Services Agency.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] The importation of a nominal amount of liquor by individuals for personal use is permitted, provided that conditions for the individual's duration of stay outside the country are satisfied.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] In 2007, Canada's first genuine absinthe (Taboo Absinthe) was created by Okanagan Spirits Craft Distillery in British Columbia.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] The European Union permits a maximum thujone level of 35 mg/kg in alcoholic beverages where *Artemisia* species is a listed ingredient, and 10 mg/kg in other alcoholic beverages.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] Member countries regulate absinthe production within this framework.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] The sale of absinthe is permitted in all EU countries unless they further regulate it.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] The sale and production of absinthe was prohibited in Finland from 1919 to 1932; no current prohibitions exist.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] The government-owned chain of liquor stores (Alko) is the only outlet that may sell alcoholic beverages containing over 8% ABV, although national law bans the sale of alcoholic beverages containing over 80% ABV.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] Édouard Manet's first major painting *The Absinthe Drinker* was controversial, and was rejected by the Paris Salon in 1859.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] French producers circumvented this regulatory obstacle by labelling absinthe as *spiritueux à base de plantes d'absinthe* ('wormwood-based spirits'), with many either reducing or omitting fennel and hyssop altogether from their products.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] A legal challenge to the scientific basis of this decree resulted in its repeal (2009), which opened the door for the official French re-legalisation of absinthe for the first time since 1915.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] The French Senate voted to repeal the prohibition in mid-April 2011.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] A ban on absinthe was enacted in Germany on 27 March 1923.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] In addition to banning the production of commercial trade in absinthe, the law went so far as to prohibit the distribution of printed matter that provided details of its production.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] The original ban was lifted in 1981, but the use of *Artemisia absinthium* as a flavouring agent remained prohibited.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] On 27 September 1991, Germany adopted the European Community's standards of 1988, which effectively re-legalised absinthe.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] The Fascist regime in 1926 banned the production, import, transport, and sale of any liquor named *Assenzio*.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] The ban was reinforced in 1931 with harsher penalties for transgressors and remained in force until 1992 when the Italian government amended its laws to comply with the EU directive 88/388/EEC.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] Although absinthe is not prohibited at the national level, some local authorities have banned it.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] The ban came in August 2008 after several issues of misuse drew public and police attention.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] One incident resulted in breathing difficulties and hospitalising of a 17-year-old for alcohol poisoning.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] The particular brand of absinthe that caused these effects was bottled at 89% ABV.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] The sale and production of absinthe has never been prohibited in Sweden or Norway.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] However, the only outlet that may sell alcoholic beverages containing more than 3.5% ABV in Sweden and 4.75% ABV in Norway is the government-owned chain of liquor stores known as Systembolaget in Sweden and Vinmonopolet in Norway.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] Systembolaget and Vinmonopolet did not import or sell absinthe for many years after the ban in France; however, today several absinthes are available for purchase in Systembolaget stores, including Swedish made distilled absinthe.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] In Norway, on the other hand, one is less likely to find many absinthes since Norwegian alcohol law prohibits the sale and importation of alcoholic beverages above 60% ABV, which eliminates most absinthes.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] In Switzerland, the sale and production of absinthe was prohibited from 1910 to 1 March 2005.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] This was based on a vote in 1908, inspired by the Jean Lanfray incident.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] To be legally made or sold in Switzerland, absinthe must be distilled, must not contain certain additives, and must be either naturally coloured or left uncoloured.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] In 2014, the Federal Administrative Court of Switzerland invalidated a governmental decision of 2010 which allowed only absinthe made in the Val-de-Travers region to be labelled as absinthe in Switzerland.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] The court found that absinthe was a label for a product and was not tied to a geographic origin.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] Absinthe was never legally prohibited in the UK, but was not imported for a 70-year period.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] In 2007, the Alcohol and Tobacco Tax and Trade Bureau (TTB) effectively lifted the long-standing absinthe ban, and it has since approved many brands for sale in the US market.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] This was made possible partly through the TTB's clarification of the Food and Drug Administration's (FDA) thujone content regulations, which specify that finished food and beverages that contain *Artemisia* species must be thujone-free.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] In this context, the TTB considers a product thujone-free if the thujone content is less than 10 ppm (equal to 10 mg/kg).
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] This is verified through the use of gas chromatography–mass spectrometry.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] The brands Kübler and Lucid and their lawyers did most of the work to get absinthe legalized in the U.S., over the 2004–2007 time period.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] In the U.S., 5 March sometimes is referred to as "National Absinthe Day", as it was the day the 95-year ban on absinthe was finally lifted.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] Absinthe imported in violation of these regulations is subject to seizure at the discretion of U.S.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] Numerous artists and writers living in France in the late 19th and early 20th centuries were noted absinthe drinkers and featured absinthe in their work.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] Some of these included Édouard Manet, Guy de Maupassant, Paul Verlaine, Amedeo Modigliani, Edgar Degas, Henri de Toulouse-Lautrec, Vincent van Gogh, Oscar Wilde, Arthur Rimbaud, and Émile Zola.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] Many other renowned artists and writers similarly drew from this cultural well, including Aleister Crowley, Ernest Hemingway, Pablo Picasso, August Strindberg, and Erik Satie.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] The aura of illicitness and mystery surrounding absinthe has played into literature, movies, music, and television, where it is often portrayed as a mysterious, addictive, and mind-altering drink.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] Marie Corelli's *Wormwood: A Drama of Paris* (1890) was a popular novel about a Frenchman driven to murder and ruin after being introduced to absinthe.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] Intended as a morality tale on the dangers of the drink, it was speculated to have contributed to subsequent bans of absinthe in Europe and the United States.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] Some of the earliest film references include *The Hasher's Delirium* (1910) by Émile Cohl, an early pioneer in the art of animation, as well as two different silent films, each titled *Absinthe*, from 1913 and 1914 respectively.
[src:arak-drink/absinthe] More recently, it served as the title of a 2018 song by the indie group I Don't Know How But They Found Me.
[src:arak-drink/abu-bakr-al-razi] A comprehensive thinker, al-Razi made fundamental and enduring contributions to various fields, which he recorded in over 200 manuscripts, and is particularly remembered for numerous advances in medicine through his observations and discoveries.
[src:arak-drink/abu-bakr-al-razi] An early proponent of experimental medicine, he became a successful doctor, and served as chief physician of Baghdad and Ray hospitals.
[src:arak-drink/abu-bakr-al-razi] As a teacher of medicine, he attracted students of all backgrounds and interests and was said to be compassionate and devoted to the service of his patients, whether rich or poor.
[src:arak-drink/abu-bakr-al-razi] Along with Thābit ibn Qurra (836–901), he was one of the first to clinically distinguish between smallpox and measles.
[src:arak-drink/abu-bakr-al-razi] Through translation, his medical works and ideas became known among medieval European practitioners and profoundly influenced medical education in the Latin West.
[src:arak-drink/abu-bakr-al-razi] Some volumes of his work *Al-Mansuri*, namely "On Surgery" and "A General Book on Therapy", became part of the medical curriculum in Western universities.
[src:arak-drink/abu-bakr-al-razi] Edward Granville Browne considers him as "probably the greatest and most original of all the Muslim physicians, and one of the most prolific as an author".
[src:arak-drink/abu-bakr-al-razi] Additionally, he has been described as the father of pediatrics, and a pioneer of obstetrics and ophthalmology.
[src:arak-drink/abu-bakr-al-razi] Al-Razi was born in the city of Ray (modern Rey, also the origin of his name "al-Razi"), into a family of Persian stock and was a native speaker of the Persian language.
[src:arak-drink/abu-bakr-al-razi] Ray was situated on the Great Silk Road that for centuries facilitated trade and cultural exchanges between East and West.
[src:arak-drink/abu-bakr-al-razi] It is located on the southern slopes of the Alborz mountain range situated near Tehran, Iran.
[src:arak-drink/abu-bakr-al-razi] In his youth, al-Razi moved to Baghdad where he studied and practiced at the local bimaristan (hospital).
[src:arak-drink/abu-bakr-al-razi] Later, he was invited back to Rey by Mansur ibn Ishaq, then the governor of Ray, and became a bimaristan's head.
[src:arak-drink/abu-bakr-al-razi] He dedicated two books on medicine to Mansur ibn Ishaq, *The Spiritual Physic* and *Al-Mansūrī on Medicine*.
[src:arak-drink/abu-bakr-al-razi] Because of his newly acquired popularity as physician, al-Razi was invited to Baghdad where he assumed the responsibilities of a director in a new hospital named after its founder al-Muʿtaḍid (d.
[src:arak-drink/abu-bakr-al-razi] Under the reign of Al-Mutadid's son, Al-Muktafi (r.
[src:arak-drink/abu-bakr-al-razi] 902–908) al-Razi was commissioned to build a new hospital, which should be the largest of the Abbasid Caliphate.
[src:arak-drink/abu-bakr-al-razi] To pick the future hospital's location, al-Razi adopted what is nowadays known as an evidence-based approach suggesting having fresh meat hung in various places throughout the city and to build the hospital where meat took longest to rot.
[src:arak-drink/abu-bakr-al-razi] He spent the last years of his life in his native Rey suffering from glaucoma.
[src:arak-drink/abu-bakr-al-razi] His eye affliction started with cataracts and ended in total blindness.
[src:arak-drink/abu-bakr-al-razi] The cause of his blindness is uncertain.
[src:arak-drink/abu-bakr-al-razi] One account mentioned by Ibn Juljul attributed the cause to a blow to his head by his patron, Mansur ibn Ishaq, for failing to provide proof for his alchemy theories; while Abulfaraj and Casiri claimed that the cause was a diet of beans only.
[src:arak-drink/abu-bakr-al-razi] Allegedly, he was approached by a physician offering an ointment to cure his blindness.
[src:arak-drink/abu-bakr-al-razi] Al-Razi then asked him how many layers does the eye contain and when he was unable to receive an answer, he declined the treatment stating "my eyes will not be treated by one who does not know the basics of its anatomy".
[src:arak-drink/abu-bakr-al-razi] The lectures of al-Razi attracted many students.
[src:arak-drink/abu-bakr-al-razi] As Ibn al-Nadim relates in *Fihrist*, al-Razi was considered a *shaikh*, an honorary title given to one entitled to teach and surrounded by several circles of students.
[src:arak-drink/abu-bakr-al-razi] When someone raised a question, it was passed on to students of the 'first circle'; if they did not know the answer, it was passed on to those of the 'second circle', and so on.
[src:arak-drink/abu-bakr-al-razi] When all students would fail to answer, al-Razi himself would consider the query.
[src:arak-drink/abu-bakr-al-razi] Al-Razi was a generous person by nature, with a considerate attitude towards his patients.
[src:arak-drink/abu-bakr-al-razi] He was charitable to the poor, treated them without payment in any form, and wrote for them a treatise *Man La Yaḥḍuruhu al-Ṭabīb*, or *Who Has No Physician to Attend Him*, with medical advice.
[src:arak-drink/abu-bakr-al-razi] One former pupil from Tabaristan came to look after him, but as al-Biruni wrote, al-Razi rewarded him for his intentions and sent him back home, proclaiming that his final days were approaching.
[src:arak-drink/abu-bakr-al-razi] According to Biruni, al-Razi died in Rey in 925 at sixty years of age.
[src:arak-drink/abu-bakr-al-razi] Biruni, who considered al-Razi his mentor, among the first penned a short biography of al-Razi including a bibliography of his numerous works.
[src:arak-drink/abu-bakr-al-razi] Ibn al-Nadim recorded an account by al-Razi of a Chinese student who copied down all of Galen's works in Chinese as al-Razi read them to him out loud after the student learned fluent Arabic in 5 months and attended al-Razi's lectures.
[src:arak-drink/abu-bakr-al-razi] After his death, his fame spread beyond the Middle East to Medieval Europe, and lived on.
[src:arak-drink/abu-bakr-al-razi] In an undated catalog of the library at Peterborough Abbey, most likely from the 14th century, al-Razi is listed as a part author of ten books on medicine.
[src:arak-drink/abu-bakr-al-razi] Al-Razi was one of the world's first great medical experts.
[src:arak-drink/abu-bakr-al-razi] He is considered the father of psychology and psychotherapy.
[src:arak-drink/abu-bakr-al-razi] Al-Razi's book *al-Judari wa l-ḥaṣba* "On Smallpox and Measles", is, along with a book of the same name by Thabit ibn Qurra (836–901), among the earliest extant books describing smallpox and measles as distinct diseases.
[src:arak-drink/abu-bakr-al-razi] Smallpox was not known in ancient Greek medicine.
[src:arak-drink/abu-bakr-al-razi] It was likely differentiated from measles and other similar diseases by authors in late antiquity writing in Medieval Greek and Syriac, whose works were known to Thabit and al-Razi.
[src:arak-drink/abu-bakr-al-razi] Al-Razi's work was translated into Syriac and then into Greek.
[src:arak-drink/abu-bakr-al-razi] It became known in Europe through this translation, as well as Latin translations based on the Greek text, and was later translated into several European languages.
[src:arak-drink/abu-bakr-al-razi] Neither the date nor the author of the Syriac and Greek versions is known, but the Greek was created at the request of one of the Byzantine emperors.
[src:arak-drink/abu-bakr-al-razi] The anonymous Greek translator of Razi's work used the term λοιμική (*loimikē*) to describe smallpox, since the ancient Greek language had no word that precisely conveyed this meaning.
[src:arak-drink/abu-bakr-al-razi] Al-Razi compared the outcome of patients with meningitis treated with blood-letting with the outcome of those treated without it to see if blood-letting could help.
[src:arak-drink/abu-bakr-al-razi] Al-Razi contributed in many ways to the early practice of pharmacy by compiling texts, in which he introduces the use of "mercurial ointments" and his development of apparatus such as mortars, flasks, spatulas and phials, which were used in pharmacies until the early twentieth century.
[src:arak-drink/abu-bakr-al-razi] On a professional level, al-Razi introduced many practical, progressive, medical and psychological ideas.
[src:arak-drink/abu-bakr-al-razi] He attacked charlatans and fake doctors who roamed the cities and countryside selling their nostrums and "cures".
[src:arak-drink/abu-bakr-al-razi] At the same time, he warned that even highly educated doctors did not have the answers to all medical problems and could not cure all sicknesses or heal every disease, which was humanly speaking impossible.
[src:arak-drink/abu-bakr-al-razi] To become more useful in their services and truer to their calling, al-Razi advised practitioners to keep up with advanced knowledge by continually studying medical books and exposing themselves to new information.
[src:arak-drink/abu-bakr-al-razi] He made a distinction between curable and incurable diseases.
[src:arak-drink/abu-bakr-al-razi] Pertaining to the latter, he commented that in the case of advanced cases of cancer and leprosy the physician should not be blamed when he could not cure them.
[src:arak-drink/abu-bakr-al-razi] To add a humorous note, al-Razi felt great pity for physicians who took care for the well-being of princes, nobility, and women, because they did not obey the doctor's orders to restrict their diet or get medical treatment, thus making it most difficult being their physician.
[src:arak-drink/abu-bakr-al-razi] Arabic: الحاوي, romanized: *al-Hāwi*, lit.
[src:arak-drink/abu-bakr-al-razi] 'The Comprehensive [Book on Medicine]' This 23-volume medical textbook sets the foundation of gynecology, obstetrics, oncology and chemotherapy, and ophthalmic surgery.
[src:arak-drink/abu-bakr-al-razi] It also contains considerations and criticism on Aristotle and Plato and expresses innovative views on many subjects.
[src:arak-drink/abu-bakr-al-razi] Because of this book alone, many scholars consider al-Razi the greatest medical doctor of the Middle Ages.
[src:arak-drink/abu-bakr-al-razi] Al-Razi was possibly the first Persian doctor to deliberately write a home medical manual (remedial) directed at the general public.
[src:arak-drink/abu-bakr-al-razi] He dedicated it to the poor, the traveller, and the ordinary citizen who could consult it to treat common ailments when a doctor was unavailable.
[src:arak-drink/abu-bakr-al-razi] This book is of special interest to the history of pharmacy since similar books were very popular until the 20th century.
[src:arak-drink/abu-bakr-al-razi] Al-Razi described in its 36 chapters diets and drug components that can be found in either an apothecary, a marketplace, in well-equipped kitchens, or military camps.
[src:arak-drink/abu-bakr-al-razi] Thus, every intelligent person could follow its instructions and prepare the proper recipes with good results.
[src:arak-drink/abu-bakr-al-razi] Some of the illnesses treated were headaches, colds, coughing, melancholy and diseases of the eye, ear, and stomach.
[src:arak-drink/abu-bakr-al-razi] For example, he prescribed for a feverish headache: "2 parts of *duhn* (oily extract) of rose, to be mixed with 1 part of vinegar, in which a piece of linen cloth is dipped and compressed on the forehead".
[src:arak-drink/abu-bakr-al-razi] He recommended as a laxative, "7 drams of dried violet flowers with 20 pears, macerated and well mixed, then strained.
[src:arak-drink/abu-bakr-al-razi] Add to this filtrate 20 drams of sugar for a drink." In cases of melancholy, he invariably recommended prescriptions, which included either poppies or its juice (opium), *Cuscuta epithymum* (clover dodder) or both.
[src:arak-drink/abu-bakr-al-razi] For an eye-remedy, he advised myrrh, saffron, and frankincense, 2 drams each, to be mixed with 1 dram of yellow arsenic formed into tablets.
[src:arak-drink/abu-bakr-al-razi] Each tablet was to be dissolved in sufficient coriander water and used as eye drops.
[src:arak-drink/abu-bakr-al-razi] Al-Razi dedicated this work to his patron Abū Ṣāliḥ al-Manṣūr, the Samanid governor of Ray.
[src:arak-drink/abu-bakr-al-razi] It was translated into Latin by Gerard of Cremona around 1180.
[src:arak-drink/abu-bakr-al-razi] A Latin translation of it was edited in the 16th century by the Dutch anatomist and physician Andreas Vesalius.
[src:arak-drink/abu-bakr-al-razi] In his book *Doubts about Galen*, al-Razi rejects several claims made by the Greek physician, as far as the alleged superiority of the Greek language and many of his cosmological and medical views.
[src:arak-drink/abu-bakr-al-razi] He links medicine with philosophy, and states that sound practice demands independent thinking.
[src:arak-drink/abu-bakr-al-razi] He reports that Galen's descriptions do not agree with his own clinical observations regarding the run of a fever.
[src:arak-drink/abu-bakr-al-razi] And in some cases he finds that his clinical experience exceeds Galen's.
[src:arak-drink/abu-bakr-al-razi] He criticized Galen's theory that the body possessed four separate "humors" whose balance is the key to health and a natural body temperature.
[src:arak-drink/abu-bakr-al-razi] A sure way to upset such a system was to insert a liquid with a different temperature into the body, resulting in an increase or decrease of bodily heat, which resembled the temperature of that particular fluid.
[src:arak-drink/abu-bakr-al-razi] Al-Razi noted that a warm drink would heat the body much higher than its natural temperature.
[src:arak-drink/abu-bakr-al-razi] Thus, the drink would trigger a response from the body rather than transferring only its warmth or coldness to it.
[src:arak-drink/abu-bakr-al-razi] This line of criticism could completely refute Galen's theory of humors and Aristotle's theory of the classical elements on which it was grounded.
[src:arak-drink/abu-bakr-al-razi] Al-Razi's alchemical experiments suggested other qualities of matter, such as "oiliness" and "sulphurousness", or inflammability and salinity, which were not readily explained by the traditional fire, water, earth, and air division of elements.
[src:arak-drink/abu-bakr-al-razi] Al-Razi's challenge to the current fundamentals of medical theory was quite controversial.
[src:arak-drink/abu-bakr-al-razi] Al-Razi's *The Diseases of Children* was the first monograph to deal with pediatrics as an independent field of medicine.
[src:arak-drink/abu-bakr-al-razi] Al-Razi's interest in alchemy and his strong belief in the possibility of transmutation of lesser metals to silver and gold was attested half a century after his death by Ibn an-Nadim's book, *The Philosopher's Stone* (*Lapis Philosophorum* in Latin).
[src:arak-drink/abu-bakr-al-razi] Nadim attributed a series of twelve books to al-Razi, plus an additional seven, including his refutation to al-Kindi's denial of the validity of alchemy.
[src:arak-drink/abu-bakr-al-razi] Al-Kindi (801–873 CE) had been appointed by the Abbasid Caliph Ma'mun founder of Baghdad, to 'the House of Wisdom' in that city, he was a philosopher and an opponent of alchemy.
[src:arak-drink/abu-bakr-al-razi] Al-Razi's two best-known alchemical texts, which largely superseded his earlier ones: *al-Asrar* (الاسرار "The Secrets"), and *Sirr al-Asrar* (سر الاسرار "The Secret of Secrets"), which incorporates much of the previous work.
[src:arak-drink/abu-bakr-al-razi] Apparently al-Razi's contemporaries believed that he had obtained the secret of turning iron and copper into gold.
[src:arak-drink/abu-bakr-al-razi] Biographer Khosro Moetazed reports in *Mohammad Zakaria Razi* that a certain General Simjur confronted al-Razi in public, and asked whether that was the underlying reason for his willingness to treat patients without a fee.
[src:arak-drink/abu-bakr-al-razi] Al-Razi's works present the first systematic classification of carefully observed and verified facts regarding chemical substances, reactions and apparatus, described in a language almost entirely free from mysticism and ambiguity.
[src:arak-drink/abu-bakr-al-razi] Here he gives systematic attention to basic chemical operations important to the history of pharmacy.
[src:arak-drink/abu-bakr-al-razi] In this book al-Razi divides the subject of "matter' into three categories, as in his previous book *Al-Asrar*.
[src:arak-drink/abu-bakr-al-razi] Knowledge of equipment and tools of interest to and used by either alchemists or apothecaries.
[src:arak-drink/abu-bakr-al-razi] Knowledge of seven alchemical procedures and techniques: sublimation and condensation of mercury, precipitation of sulfur, and arsenic calcination of minerals (gold, silver, copper, lead, and iron), salts, glass, talc, shells, and waxing.
[src:arak-drink/abu-bakr-al-razi] Similar to the commentary on the 8th century text on amalgams ascribed to Jabir ibn Hayyan, al-Razi gives methods and procedures of coloring a silver object to imitate gold (gold leafing) and the reverse technique of removing its color back to silver.
[src:arak-drink/abu-bakr-al-razi] Gilding and silvering of other metals (alum, calcium salts, iron, copper, and tutty) are also described, as well as how colors will last for years without tarnishing or changing.
[src:arak-drink/abu-bakr-al-razi] Seven bodies (*al-ajsad*): silver, gold, copper, iron, black lead (*plumbago*), zinc (*kharsind*), and tin.
[src:arak-drink/abu-bakr-al-razi] Seven vitriols (*al-zajat*): alum (*al-shabb* الشب), and white (*qalqadis* القلقديس), black, red (*suri* السوري), and yellow (*qulqutar* القلقطار) vitriols (the impure sulfates of iron, copper, etc.), green (*qalqand* القلقند).
[src:arak-drink/abu-bakr-al-razi] Seven borates: natron, and impure sodium borate.
[src:arak-drink/abu-bakr-al-razi] Eleven salts (*al-amlah*): including brine, common salt, ashes, naphtha, live lime, and urine, rock, and sea salts.
[src:arak-drink/abu-bakr-al-razi] Then he separately defines and describes each of these substances, the best forms and colours of each, and the qualities of various adulterations.
[src:arak-drink/abu-bakr-al-razi] Al-Razi gives also a list of apparatus used in alchemy.
[src:arak-drink/abu-bakr-al-razi] Although al-Razi wrote extensively on philosophy, most of his works on this subject are now lost.
[src:arak-drink/abu-bakr-al-razi] Most of his religio-philosophical ideas, including his belief in five "eternal principles", are only known from fragments and testimonies found in other authors, who were often strongly opposed to his thought.
[src:arak-drink/abu-bakr-al-razi] Al-Razi's metaphysical doctrine derives from the theory of the "five eternals", according to which the world is produced out of an interaction between God and four other eternal principles (soul, matter, time, and place).
[src:arak-drink/abu-bakr-al-razi] He accepted a pre-socratic type of atomism of the bodies, and for that he differed from both the falasifa and the mutakallimun.
[src:arak-drink/abu-bakr-al-razi] While he was influenced by Plato and the medical writers, mainly Galen, he rejected taqlid and thus expressed criticism about some of their views.
[src:arak-drink/abu-bakr-al-razi] This is evident from the title of one of his works, *Doubts About Galen*.
[src:arak-drink/abu-bakr-al-razi] A number of contradictory works and statements about religion have been ascribed to al-Razi.
[src:arak-drink/abu-bakr-al-razi] Many sources claim that al-Razi viewed prophecy and revealed religion as unnecessary and delusional, claiming that all humans have the ability to access and discover truth (including the existence of God) through God-given reason.
[src:arak-drink/abu-bakr-al-razi] Because of his supposed rejection of prophecy and acceptance of reason as the primary method for accessing the truth, al-Razi came to be admired as a freethinker by some.
[src:arak-drink/abu-bakr-al-razi] According to al-Biruni's *Bibliography of al-Razi* (*Risāla fī Fihrist Kutub al-Rāzī*), al-Razi wrote two "heretical books": "*Fī al-Nubuwwāt* (*On Prophecies*) and "*Fī Ḥiyal al-Mutanabbīn* (*On the Tricks of False Prophets*).
[src:arak-drink/abu-bakr-al-razi] None of his works on religion is now extant in full.
[src:arak-drink/abu-bakr-al-razi] Sarah Stroumsa has argued that al-Razi was a freethinker who rejected all revealed religions.
[src:arak-drink/abu-bakr-al-razi] However, Peter Adamson, Marwan Rashed and others hold that al-Razi did not reject revealed religion, on the basis of more recent evidence found in the writings of the theologian and philosopher Fakhr al-Din al-Razi (died 1210).
[src:arak-drink/abu-bakr-al-razi] The views and quotes that are often ascribed to al-Razi where he appears to be critical of religion are found in a book written by Abu Hatim al-Razi, called *Aʿlām al-nubuwwa* (Signs of Prophecy), which documents a debate between Abu Hatim and al-Razi.
[src:arak-drink/abu-bakr-al-razi] Abu Hatim was an Isma'ili missionary who debated al-Razi, but whether he has faithfully recorded the views of al-Razi is disputed.
[src:arak-drink/abu-bakr-al-razi] According to Abdul Latif al-'Abd, Islamic philosophy professor at Cairo University, Abu Hatim and his student, Ḥamīd al-dīn Karmānī (d. after 411AH/1020CE), were Isma'ili extremists who often misrepresented the views of al-Razi in their works.
[src:arak-drink/abu-bakr-al-razi] This view is also corroborated by early historians like al-Shahrastani who noted "that such accusations should be doubted since they were made by Ismāʿīlīs, who had been severely attacked by Muḥammad ibn Zakariyyā Rāzī".
[src:arak-drink/abu-bakr-al-razi] Al-'Abd points out that the views allegedly expressed by al-Razi contradict what is found in al-Razi's own works, like the *Spiritual Medicine* (*Fī al-ṭibb al-rūḥānī*).
[src:arak-drink/abu-bakr-al-razi] Peter Adamson concurs that Abu Hatim may have "deliberately misdescribed" al-Razi's position as a rejection of Islam and revealed religions.
[src:arak-drink/abu-bakr-al-razi] Instead, al-Razi was only arguing against the use of miracles to prove Muhammad's prophecy, anthropomorphism, and the uncritical acceptance of *taqlīd* vs *naẓar*.
[src:arak-drink/abu-bakr-al-razi] Adamson points out to a work by Fakhr al-din al-Razi where al-Razi is quoted as citing the Quran and the prophets to support his views.
[src:arak-drink/abu-bakr-al-razi] In contrast, earlier historians such as Paul Kraus and Sarah Stroumsa accepted that the extracts found in Abu Hatim's book were either said by al-Razi during a debate or were quoted from a now lost work.
[src:arak-drink/abu-bakr-al-razi] According to the debate with Abu Hatim, al-Razi denied the validity of prophecy or other authority figures, and rejected prophetic miracles.
[src:arak-drink/abu-bakr-al-razi] He also directed a scathing critique on revealed religions and the miraculous quality of the Quran.
[src:arak-drink/abu-bakr-al-razi] They suggest that this lost work is either his famous *al-ʿIlm al-Ilāhī* or another shorter independent work called *Makharīq al-Anbiyāʾ* (*The Prophets' Fraudulent Tricks*).
[src:arak-drink/abu-bakr-al-razi] Abu Hatim, however, did not explicitly mention al-Razi by name in his book, but referred to his interlocutor simply as the *mulḥid* (lit.
[src:arak-drink/abu-bakr-al-razi] Al-Razi's religious and philosophical views were later criticized by Abu Rayhan Biruni and Avicenna in the early 11th century.
[src:arak-drink/abu-bakr-al-razi] Biruni in particular wrote a short treatise (*risala*) dealing with al-Razi, criticizing him for his sympathy with Manichaeism, his Hermetical writings, his religious and philosophical views, for refusing to mathematize physics, and his active opposition to mathematics.
[src:arak-drink/abu-bakr-al-razi] Avicenna, who was himself a physician and philosopher, also criticized al-Razi.
[src:arak-drink/abu-bakr-al-razi] Nasr-i-Khosraw posthumously accused him of having plagiarized Iranshahri, whom Khosraw considered the master of al-Razi.
[src:arak-drink/abu-bakr-al-razi] The modern-day Razi Institute in Karaj and Razi University in Kermanshah were named after him.
[src:arak-drink/abu-bakr-al-razi] A "Razi Day" ("Pharmacy Day") is commemorated in Iran every 27 August.
[src:arak-drink/abu-bakr-al-razi] In June 2009, Iran donated a "Scholars Pavilion" or Chartagi to the United Nations Office in Vienna, now placed in the central Memorial Plaza of the Vienna International Center.
[src:arak-drink/abu-bakr-al-razi] The pavilion features the statues of al-Razi, Avicenna, Abu Rayhan Biruni, and Omar Khayyam.
[src:arak-drink/abu-bakr-al-razi] George Sarton remarked him as "greatest physician of Islam and the Medieval Ages".
[src:arak-drink/acerum] In the 1970s, distillers began to produce alcohol from maple syrup.
[src:arak-drink/acerum] Although some distilled alcohol tests were then carried out in university laboratories, it was not until the 1990s that certain maple syrup producers began to produce a wine based on this sweet resource, which was initially called Acer.
[src:arak-drink/acerum] One of the first producers of Acerum was The Domaine Acer, based in Témiscouata, Quebec.
[src:arak-drink/acerum] When Vallier Robert took the reins of his family maple business in 1990, he quickly saw the potential to make alcohol.
[src:arak-drink/acerum] In 1996, the maple farmer was granted the first licence to produce artisanal maple-based alcoholic beverages.
[src:arak-drink/acerum] He began creating several varieties of maple sap wine, including dry, sparkling and dessert wines.
[src:arak-drink/acerum] During the same period, some distilleries began to market maple eau-de-vie, but it was not until December 2017 that the name Acerum appeared for the first time for a maple eau-de-vie.
[src:arak-drink/acerum] As defined by the specifications of the UDSÉ, Acerum must be entirely manufactured in the province of Quebec, in Canada, with maple syrup, maple concentrate, or maple sap from Quebec maples.
[src:arak-drink/advocaat] Two theories have been put out on the origins of "advocaat".
[src:arak-drink/advocaat] According to several makers, such as Verpoorten and Bols, and the *Oxford Companion to Sugar and Sweets*, its origins can be traced back to "abacate", an alcoholic beverage of the indigenous people in Brazil, which was made with avocado.
[src:arak-drink/advocaat] Dutch colonials of northern Brazil introduced this beverage to Europe as "advocat/advocaat".
[src:arak-drink/advocaat] As avocados could not grow in northern Europe, they were replaced with egg yolk, thought to have a similar taste and consistency, and the name derived from the avocado stuck, although the drink no longer contains any.
[src:arak-drink/advocaat] Cooymans started a distillery in downtown 's-Hertogenbosch.
[src:arak-drink/advocaat] There he developed the egg drink "advocaat".
[src:arak-drink/advocaat] In 1876, the Antwerp distiller Eugen Verpoorten established a distillery in Heinsberg near Aachen, Germany, which made an egg liqueur (*Eierlikör* in German) using eggs, sugar, distilled alcohol, and other ingredients.
[src:arak-drink/advocaat] Jars and wide mouth bottles of thick advocaat are sold mainly in the Netherlands and Belgium, though may be available in Germany, Austria, and South Africa.
[src:arak-drink/advocaat] Further exports are of a more liquid version.
[src:arak-drink/advocaat] In particular the original thick variety, i.e., without albumen, is used as a waffle, pancake or poffertjes topping, as an ingredient in ice cream, custards, pastries and similar desserts, or as an apéritif or digestif.
[src:arak-drink/advocaat] The latter, possibly topped with whipped cream and then occasionally sprinkled with a touch of cocoa powder, is served in a very tiny bowl or small glass from which it is eaten by use of a teaspoon.
[src:arak-drink/advocaat] In Belgian restaurants and taverns, it may be a complementary accompaniment to a coffee.
[src:arak-drink/advocaat] In the export variety both parts of the eggs are used.
[src:arak-drink/advocaat] A popular cocktail using advocaat is the Snowball: a mixture of advocaat, sparkling lemonade and sometimes (although this is not required) lime juice that is often consumed at Christmas time.
[src:arak-drink/advocaat] Another is the Fluffy duck, made with rum.
[src:arak-drink/advocaat] Another advocaat-based beverage is the Bombardino, a drink commonly found in Italian ski resorts, particularly the Italian Alps, made by mixing advocaat, brandy, and whipped cream.
[src:arak-drink/advocaat] The Polish equivalent, *ajerkoniak* (German: *eier* 'eggs' and French: *cognac*), is based on vodka instead of brandy, despite what the name may suggest.
[src:arak-drink/agave] Many plants in this genus may be considered perennial, because they require several to many years to mature and flower.
[src:arak-drink/agave] However, most *Agave* species are more accurately described as monocarpic rosettes or multiannuals, since each individual rosette flowers only once and then dies; a small number of *Agave* species are polycarpic.
[src:arak-drink/agave] Along with plants from the closely related genera *Yucca*, *Hesperoyucca*, and *Hesperaloe,* various *Agave* species are popular ornamental plants in hot, dry climates, as they require very little supplemental water to survive.
[src:arak-drink/agave] Some *Agave* species are known by the common name "century plant".
[src:arak-drink/agave] In other regions, it goes by different names.
[src:arak-drink/agave] In the Chinese, Japanese, and Korean languages, it is referred to as the compound word *dragon tongue orchid* (simplified Chinese: 龙舌兰; traditional Chinese: 龍舌蘭; pinyin: *lóngshélán*; Japanese: 竜舌蘭, romanized: *ryūzetsuran*; Korean: 용설란; Hanja: 龍舌蘭; RR: *yongseollan*).
[src:arak-drink/agave] In Malta, it is referred to as *Sabbara*; In Maltese, Agave americana is referred to as "Sabbara tal-Amerika", and Agave sisalana is referred to as "Sabbara ta' Sisal".
[src:arak-drink/agave] The succulent leaves of most *Agave* species have sharp marginal teeth, an extremely sharp terminal spine, and are very fibrous inside.
[src:arak-drink/agave] The stout stem is usually extremely short, which may make the plant appear as though it is stemless.
[src:arak-drink/agave] Agaves can be confused with cacti, aloes, or stonecrops, but although these plants all share similar morphological adaptations to arid environments (e.g. succulence), each group belongs to a different plant family and probably experienced convergent evolution.
[src:arak-drink/agave] Further, cactus (Cactaceae) and stonecrop (Crassulaceae) lineages are eudicots, while aloes (Asphodelaceae) and agaves (Asparagaceae) are monocots.
[src:arak-drink/agave] The agave root system, consisting of a network of shallow rhizomes, allows the agave to efficiently capture moisture from rain, condensation, and dew.
[src:arak-drink/agave] In addition to growing from seeds, most agaves produce 'pups' – young plants from runners.
[src:arak-drink/agave] *Agave vilmoriniana* (the octopus agave) produces hundreds of pups on its bloom stalk.
[src:arak-drink/agave] Agave leaves store the plant's water and are crucial to its continued existence.
[src:arak-drink/agave] The coated leaf surface prevents evaporation.
[src:arak-drink/agave] The leaves also have sharp, spiked edges.
[src:arak-drink/agave] The spikes discourage predators from eating the plant or using it as a source of water and are so tough that ancient peoples used them for sewing needles.
[src:arak-drink/agave] Some agaves bloom at a height up to 9 m (30 ft) so that they are far out of reach to animals that might attack them.
[src:arak-drink/agave] Smaller species, such as *Agave lechuguilla*, have smaller bloom stalks.
[src:arak-drink/agave] The genus name *Agave* come from the Ancient Greek αγαυή *agauê* from ἀγαυός *agauós* meaning "illustrious, noble" having to do with very tall flower spikes found on its many species.
[src:arak-drink/agave] The genus *Agave* was erected by Carl Linnaeus in 1753, initially with four species.
[src:arak-drink/agave] The first listed was *Agave americana*, now the type species.
[src:arak-drink/agave] In the Cronquist system and others, *Agave* was placed in the family Liliaceae, but phylogenetic analyses of DNA sequences later showed it did not belong there.
[src:arak-drink/agave] In the APG II system, *Agave* was placed in the segregated family Agavaceae.
[src:arak-drink/agave] When this system was superseded by the APG III system in 2009, the Agavaceae were subsumed into the expanded family Asparagaceae, and *Agave* was treated as one of 18 genera in the subfamily Agavoideae, a position retained in the APG IV system of 2016.
[src:arak-drink/agave] However, Agavaceae had regained its taxonomic status as an independent family by 2020.
[src:arak-drink/agave] Agaves and close relatives have long presented significant taxonomic difficulty.
[src:arak-drink/agave] These difficulties could be due to the relatively young evolutionary age of the group (major diversification events of the group most likely occurred 8–10 million years ago), ease of hybridization between species (and even genera), incomplete lineage sorting, and long generation times.
[src:arak-drink/agave] Within a species, morphological variations can be considerable, especially in cultivation; many named species may be variants of original wild-type species that horticulturalists bred to appear unique in cultivation.
[src:arak-drink/agave] With the advent of DNA sequencing, new karyologic and evolutionary phylogenetic studies showed that the genera *Manfreda*, *Polianthes* and *Prochnyanthes* were genetically nested within the traditional circumscription of *Agave*, rendering the genus paraphyletic.
[src:arak-drink/agave] Early in the 21st century, these new phylogenetic results led to a reclassification of to include *Manfreda*, *Polianthes* and *Prochnyanthes* together as *Agave* subgenus *Manfreda*.
[src:arak-drink/agave] There was reaction against the changes from those who noted that the large morphological differences between the genera in this new *Agave* s.l. making them "counter-intuitive from a horticultural point of view".
[src:arak-drink/agave] *Manfreda* morphologically differs from the classic *Agave* description in being herbaceous and bulbous, while *Polianthes* are deciduous with narrow leaves and no spines.
[src:arak-drink/agave] Mexican taxonomists have continued to adhere to the traditional classifications and have published new species of *Polianthes*.
[src:arak-drink/agave] Thus, based on a wider consideration of previously established genetic, morphological, and estimated genetic divergence times, Vázquez-García et al. proposed a narrower circumscription of *Agave* by creating three new genera: *Echinoagave*, *Paleoagave* and *Paraagave*.
[src:arak-drink/agave] These new genera have gained some acceptance, and pave the way for a reconsideration of *Manfreda*, *Polianthes* and *Prochnyanthes*.
[src:arak-drink/agave] Some commonly grown species include *Agave americana*, *A. angustifolia*, *A. attenuata*, *A. murpheyi*, *A. palmeri*, *A. parryi*, *A. parviflora*, *A. tequilana*, *A. victoriae-reginae*, and *A. vilmoriniana*.
[src:arak-drink/agave] One of the most familiar species is *A. americana*, a native of tropical America.
[src:arak-drink/agave] Common names include century plant, *maguey* (in Mexico), or American aloe (though not related to the genus *Aloe*).
[src:arak-drink/agave] The name "century plant" refers to the long time the plant takes to flower.
[src:arak-drink/agave] The number of years before flowering occurs depends on the vigor of the individual plant, the richness of the soil, and the climate; during these years, the plant is storing in its fleshy leaves the nourishment required for the effort of flowering.
[src:arak-drink/agave] Some species contain components in their juice which can cause dermatitis for some people.
[src:arak-drink/agave] The ethnobotany of the agave was described by William H.
[src:arak-drink/agave] The four major edible parts of the agave are the flowers, the leaves, the stalks or basal rosettes, and the sap (in Spanish: *aguamiel*, meaning "honey water").
[src:arak-drink/agave] The sap of some species can also be used as soap.
[src:arak-drink/agave] Each agave plant produces several pounds of edible flowers during its final season.
[src:arak-drink/agave] The stalks, which are ready during the summer, before the blossom, weigh several pounds each.
[src:arak-drink/agave] Roasted, they are sweet and can be chewed to extract the sap or *aguamiel*, like sugarcane.
[src:arak-drink/agave] When dried out, the stalks can be used to make didgeridoos.
[src:arak-drink/agave] The leaves may be collected in winter and spring, when the plants are rich in sap, for eating.
[src:arak-drink/agave] The leaves of several species also yield fiber, for instance, *A. sisalana*, the sisal hemp, and *A. decipiens*, the false sisal hemp.
[src:arak-drink/agave] *A. americana* is the source of pita fiber, and is used as a fiber plant in Mexico, the West Indies, and southern Europe.
[src:arak-drink/agave] The agave, especially *A. murpheyi*, was a major food source for the prehistoric indigenous people of the Southwestern United States.
[src:arak-drink/agave] The Hohokam of southern Arizona cultivated large areas of agave.
[src:arak-drink/agave] The Navajo similarly found many uses for the agave plant.
[src:arak-drink/agave] A beverage is squeezed from the baked fibers, and the heads can be baked or boiled, pounded into flat sheets, sun dried, and stored for future use.
[src:arak-drink/agave] The baked, dried heads are also boiled and made into an edible paste, eaten whole, or made into soup.
[src:arak-drink/agave] The leaves are eaten boiled, and the young, tender flowering stalks and shoots are roasted and eaten as well.
[src:arak-drink/agave] The fibers are used to make rope, the leaves are used to line baking pits, and the sharp-pointed leaf tips are used to make basketry awls.
[src:arak-drink/agave] During the development of the inflorescence, sap rushes to the base of the young flower stalk.
[src:arak-drink/agave] Agave syrup (commonly called agave nectar), a sweetener derived from the sap, is used as an alternative to sugar in cooking, and can be added to breakfast cereals as a binding agent.
[src:arak-drink/agave] Extracts from agave leaves are under preliminary research for their potential use as food additives.
[src:arak-drink/agave] The sap of *A. americana* and other species is used in Mexico and Mesoamerica to produce pulque, an alcoholic beverage.
[src:arak-drink/agave] The flower shoot is cut out and the sap collected and subsequently fermented.
[src:arak-drink/agave] By distillation, a spirit called mezcal is prepared; one of the best-known forms of mezcal is tequila.
[src:arak-drink/agave] *azul* is used in the production of tequila.
[src:arak-drink/agave] *A. angustifolia* is widely used in the production of mezcal and pulque, though at least 10 other *Agave* species are also known to be used for this.
[src:arak-drink/agave] Agave can be used as the raw material for industrial production of fructans as a prebiotic dietary fiber.
[src:arak-drink/agave] Agave contains fructooligosaccharides, which are naturally occurring oligosaccharides that support safely subjecting peanut-allergic people to allergen immunotherapy.
[src:arak-drink/agave] Resulting from its natural habitat in stressful environments, agave is under preliminary research for its potential use in germplasm conservation and in biotechnology to better anticipate the economic effects of global climate change.
[src:arak-drink/agave] It may also have use as a bioethanol or bioenergy feedstock.
[src:arak-drink/agave] Agave plantations have potential applications on marginal lands unsuitable for grain crops.
[src:arak-drink/agence-france-presse] AFP's mission is to provide fast, comprehensive, impartial, and verified coverage of global events across all fields and formats, including video, photography, text, infographic, and audio.
[src:arak-drink/agence-france-presse] It collects, verifies, cross-checks, and distributes information in a neutral, factual form, intended for direct use by all types of media (radio, television, press, websites).
[src:arak-drink/agence-france-presse] It also serves as a source and alert service for major companies and public administrations.
[src:arak-drink/agence-france-presse] AFP operates one of the world's most extensive networks of correspondents.
[src:arak-drink/agence-france-presse] With 2,400 employees representing 100 nationalities, it maintains an editorial presence in 260 cities across 150 countries.
[src:arak-drink/agence-france-presse] Its main regional headquarters are located in Nicosia, Hong Kong, Washington, D.C., and Montevideo.
[src:arak-drink/agence-france-presse] The agency publishes stories, videos, photos, and graphics in French, English, Arabic, Portuguese, Spanish, and German.
[src:arak-drink/agence-france-presse] Two-thirds of its revenue is generated from commercial activities, while the remaining one-third is funded by the French government (€113.3 million in 2022) as compensation for fulfilling its mission of general interest.
[src:arak-drink/agence-france-presse] Agence France-Presse has its origins in the Agence Havas, founded in 1835 in Paris by Charles-Louis Havas, making it the world's oldest news service.
[src:arak-drink/agence-france-presse] The agency pioneered the collection and dissemination of news as a commodity, and had established itself as a fully global concern by the late 19th century.
[src:arak-drink/agence-france-presse] Two Havas employees, Paul Julius Reuter and Bernhard Wolff, set up their own news agencies in London and Berlin respectively.
[src:arak-drink/agence-france-presse] In 1940, when German forces occupied France during World War II, the news agency was taken over by the authorities and renamed "Office français d'information" (French Information Office); only the private advertising company retained the name Havas.
[src:arak-drink/agence-france-presse] On 20 August 1944, as Allied forces moved on Paris, a group of journalists in the French Resistance seized the offices of the FIO and issued the first news dispatch from the liberated city under the name of Agence France-Presse.
[src:arak-drink/agence-france-presse] Established as a state enterprise, AFP devoted the post-war years to developing its network of international correspondents.
[src:arak-drink/agence-france-presse] One of them was the first Western journalist to report the death of the Soviet leader Joseph Stalin on 6 March 1953.
[src:arak-drink/agence-france-presse] AFP was keen to shake off its semi-official status, and on 10 January 1957, the French Parliament passed a law establishing its independence.
[src:arak-drink/agence-france-presse] Since that date, the proportion of the agency's revenues generated by subscriptions from government departments has steadily declined.
[src:arak-drink/agence-france-presse] Such subscriptions represented 115 million euros in 2011.
[src:arak-drink/agence-france-presse] In 1982, the agency began to decentralize its editorial decision-making by setting up the first of its five autonomous regional centres, in Hong Kong, then a British dependent territory.
[src:arak-drink/agence-france-presse] Each region has its own budget, administrative director and chief editor.
[src:arak-drink/agence-france-presse] In September 2007, the AFP Foundation was launched to promote higher standards of journalism worldwide.
[src:arak-drink/agence-france-presse] The Mitrokhin Archive identified six agents and two confidential KGB contacts inside Agence France-Presse who were used in Soviet operations in France.
[src:arak-drink/agence-france-presse] In 1991, AFP set up a joint venture with Extel to create a financial news service, AFX News.
[src:arak-drink/agence-france-presse] It was sold in 2006 to Thomson Financial.
[src:arak-drink/agence-france-presse] In October 2008, the Government of France announced moves to change AFP's status, including the involvement of outside investors.
[src:arak-drink/agence-france-presse] On 27 November of that year, the main trade unions represented in the company's home base of France – the CGT, Force Ouvrière, Syndicat national des journalistes, Union syndicale des journalistes CFDT and SUD, launched an online petition to oppose what they saw as an attempt to privatise the agency.
[src:arak-drink/agence-france-presse] On 10 December 2009, the French Culture Minister Frédéric Mitterrand announced that he was setting up a Committee of Experts under former AFP CEO Henri Pigeat to study plans for the agency's future status.
[src:arak-drink/agence-france-presse] On 24 February 2010, Pierre Louette unexpectedly announced his intention to resign as CEO by the end of March, and move to a job with France Télécom.
[src:arak-drink/agence-france-presse] In November 2013, AFP and Getty Images were ordered to pay $1.2 million compensation to freelance photojournalist Daniel Morel for using his images posted on Twitter related to the 2010 Haiti earthquake without his permission, in violation of copyright and Twitter's terms of service.
[src:arak-drink/agence-france-presse] AFP's statute was changed in 2015 to bring it into line with European legislation through Law No.
[src:arak-drink/agence-france-presse] The current CEO and chairman is Fabrice Fries and the Global News Director is Phil Chetwynd.
[src:arak-drink/agence-france-presse] AFP returned to profitability in 2019 for the first time since 2013 and has consistently posted positive net results every year since.
[src:arak-drink/agence-france-presse] In 2023, the net profit reached 1.1 million euros.
[src:arak-drink/agence-france-presse] The debt, which stood at 50.2 million euros at the beginning of 2017, was reduced to 26.9 million euros by the end of 2023.
[src:arak-drink/agence-france-presse] On 11 February 2025, Deputy News Director for Digital Strategy and Director of Communications Grégoire Lemarchand spoke at the AI in the City event at *École normale supérieure*, part of the AI Action Summit.
[src:arak-drink/agence-france-presse] Editorial Manager of the MediaLab Denis Teyssou participated in a roundtable discussion and Deputy News Director for Photo and Documentation Eric Baradat joined a panel discussion with representatives of Google, Microsoft and Imatag.
[src:arak-drink/agence-france-presse] On 8 May 2026, the National Communication Observatory in Niger suspended AFP due to its "repeated dissemination of content likely to seriously undermine public order, national unity, social cohesion, and the stability of republican institutions".
[src:arak-drink/agence-france-presse] The decision was criticised by the Committee to Protect Journalists as "censorship".
[src:arak-drink/agence-france-presse] AFP was voted "Best News Agency" in 2021 and 2020 by the Association for International Broadcasting (AIB).
[src:arak-drink/agence-france-presse] The Albert Londres Prize has been awarded to AFP journalists on five occasions: Patrick Meney in 1983, Sammy Ketz in 1988, AFP's Moscow office in 1995, Michel Moutot in 1999, and Emmanuel Duparcq in 2011.
[src:arak-drink/agence-france-presse] Five AFP collaborators have won the Rory Peck Prize: Pacôme Pabandji in 2014, Zein Al-Rifai in 2015, Will Vassilopoulos in 2016, Luis Sequeira in 2019, and Solan Kolli in 2021.
[src:arak-drink/agence-france-presse] The Visa d'Or (in the category News) has been awarded on four occasions to AFP photographers; Georges Gobet in 2003, Bülent Kılıç in 2015, Aris Messinis in 2016, Guillermo Arias in 2019, as well as Sameer Al-Doumy, who won the Visa d'Or Humanitaire in 2022.
[src:arak-drink/agence-france-presse] AFP was distinguished by the "Covering Climate Now Journalism Awards" in 2021 for photos taken by Josh Edelson and in 2022 (in the category "Video – Short Feature").
[src:arak-drink/agence-france-presse] In 1983, the Albert Londres Prize was awarded to Patrick Meney, who wrote a series of articles about 600 French people forcibly detained in the Gulag after World War II.
[src:arak-drink/agence-france-presse] In 1984, his book *Les Mains coupées de la Taïga* was published.
[src:arak-drink/agence-france-presse] In 1988, Sammy Ketz received the next Albert Londres Prize.
[src:arak-drink/agence-france-presse] Together with his colleague from the liberation movement, Serge Chalandon, he covered the events of the Libyan Civil War for six years.
[src:arak-drink/agence-france-presse] On 17 October 2014, AFP international director Michèle Léridon received the Investigation and Reporting Award at the International Congress of Journalism and Information.
[src:arak-drink/agence-france-presse] Michèle Léridon was the author of the article "Covering ISIS", which was posted on the agency's blog.
[src:arak-drink/agence-france-presse] In December 2014, Bülent Kılıç was named *Time* magazine Photojournalist of the Year for his coverage of events in the Middle East and Europe.
[src:arak-drink/agence-france-presse] The photographer received the same acknowledgement from *The Guardian* newspaper.
[src:arak-drink/agence-france-presse] Since 1988, the agency has its own infographics department – AFP Graphics, which creates about 70 graphics per day.
[src:arak-drink/agence-france-presse] According to the agency's website, the graphics cover these topics: 31% – politics, 27% – economics, 18% – sports, 12% – society, 10% – general news, 2% – culture and media.
[src:arak-drink/agence-france-presse] Infographics are available in six languages: French, English, Arabic, Portuguese, Spanish and German.
[src:arak-drink/agence-france-presse] In 2014, Agence France-Presse launched AFP Forum, a unified Internet platform providing access to its text, photo, video, graphic, and videographic products in six languages.
[src:arak-drink/agence-france-presse] The platform offers over 6,000 new documents daily and includes digital archives of around 40 million items.
[src:arak-drink/agence-france-presse] While clients such as newspapers, broadcasters, and online media can access full services, the general public may search and view selected materials without usage rights.
[src:arak-drink/agence-france-presse] In July 2001, the agency announced the launch of AFP Video services, a video graphics division.
[src:arak-drink/agence-france-presse] Already in 2007, the agency launches AFPTV – a project in which all news from 2011 appear in HD video format.
[src:arak-drink/agence-france-presse] As of 2015, 200 videos in 7 languages appear on the site every day.
[src:arak-drink/agence-france-presse] On 10 June 2024, AFP announced the appointment of Mehdi Lebouachera as its new Global Editor-in-Chief, effective November 2024.
[src:arak-drink/agence-france-presse] Lebouachera succeeds Sophie Huet, who held the position since 2019 and is set to transition to a new role overseeing AFP's artificial intelligence strategy.
[src:arak-drink/agence-france-presse] Lebouachera previously worked as an AFP video journalist in Central America and Mexico before becoming the Video Editor-in-Chief for Latin America in Montevideo.
[src:arak-drink/agence-france-presse] He was later appointed Global Video Editor-in-Chief in Paris and, in September 2021, assumed the role of Editor-in-Chief for the Asia-Pacific region.
[src:arak-drink/agence-france-presse] He has also worked in Nicosia, Jerusalem, Gaza and Baghdad.
[src:arak-drink/agence-france-presse] In the late 2000s, Agence France-Presse expanded its presence on mobile platforms.
[src:arak-drink/agence-france-presse] In partnership with the agency Momac, AFP launched AFP Mobile, a white-label service offering real-time news dispatches, photos, and videos for mobile portal publishers (including WAP and smartphone platforms such as the iPhone).
[src:arak-drink/agence-france-presse] According to Erik Monjalous, AFP's Commercial and Marketing Director, the publishing platform was designed to provide a complete editorial and technical solution for mobile operators.
[src:arak-drink/agence-france-presse] The service also introduced an innovative business model based on advertising revenue sharing, marking a shift in AFP's role from a traditional content provider to a full-fledged media company.
[src:arak-drink/agence-france-presse] In 2011, AFP was found liable for using photos taken from Twitter without the consent of their author, Haitian photographer Daniel Morel.
[src:arak-drink/agence-france-presse] The agency was ordered to pay $1.2 million in damages.
[src:arak-drink/agence-france-presse] In October 2017, AFP was found guilty of libel against the Front National.
[src:arak-drink/agence-france-presse] In 2016, the agency had falsely attributed fraudulent tax practices to the party in connection with the Panama Papers scandal.
[src:arak-drink/agence-france-presse] On February 10, 2025, one of its journalists filed a criminal complaint for workplace abuse against AFP.
[src:arak-drink/agence-france-presse] Separately, France’s Labor Inspectorate referred around twenty additional potential cases to prosecutors.
[src:arak-drink/agence-france-presse] In July 2025, a preliminary investigation was opened.
[src:arak-drink/agence-france-presse] AFP operates under a 1957 law as a commercial business independent of the French government.
[src:arak-drink/agence-france-presse] The board elects the CEO for a renewable term of three years.
[src:arak-drink/agence-france-presse] AFP also has a council charged with ensuring that the agency operates according to its statutes, which mandate absolute independence and neutrality.
[src:arak-drink/agence-france-presse] Editorially, AFP is governed by a network of senior journalists.
[src:arak-drink/agence-france-presse] AFP employs 2,600 staff from more than 100 nationalities, working across 150 countries and over 260 locations worldwide.
[src:arak-drink/arak-drink] Arak is traditionally made of grapes and aniseed (the seeds of the anise plant); when crushed, their oil provides arak with a slight licorice taste.
[src:arak-drink/arak-drink] Dates, figs, and other fruits are sometimes added.
[src:arak-drink/arak-drink] Typically, arak is a minimum of 50% alcohol by volume (ABV), and can be up to 70% ABV (140 proof).
[src:arak-drink/arak-drink] The word *arak* comes from Arabic **ʿaraq** (عرق), meaning 'perspiration' or 'sweat', but also 'distillate'.
[src:arak-drink/arak-drink] Its pronunciation varies depending on the regional varieties of Arabic, e.g.: [ˈʕæræʔ] or [ˈʕæræɡ].
[src:arak-drink/arak-drink] Arak is the name for distilled spirits made in the Middle East from a base of grapes or pomace with anise.
[src:arak-drink/arak-drink] These are distinct from arrack, derived from same word, but referring to spirits made in southern and southeastern Asia from distilled wines of various other bases.
[src:arak-drink/arak-drink] Arab/Persian and Islamic alchemists, like Jabir Ibn Hayyan, experimented to produce distilled alcohol for medicinal purposes.
[src:arak-drink/arak-drink] Alcohol (*al-kuhl*) and alembic (*al-inbiq*) are Arabic loanwords to several languages, as a result of the success of these experiments, though the invention and use of alcohol long predates distillation.
[src:arak-drink/arak-drink] The first to record a recipe for a distilled spirit (ethanol) was Al-Razi in the 10th century, and the distillate he made was called *arak* and was intended for use as an antiseptic and medical solvent.
[src:arak-drink/arak-drink] While extracted from grapes (and also dates and grains), it had a much higher alcohol content than wine.
[src:arak-drink/arak-drink] Despite prohibitions against the imbibing of alcohol in Islam, as the use of the spirit and distillation method spread throughout the Islamic world, it was also used recreationally.
[src:arak-drink/arak-drink] The 1936 book *Arbeit und Sitte in Palaestina* ("Work and Customs in Palestine") by German orientalist Gustaf Dalman described a preparation method for arak that uses grapes and anise seeds which he learned in the Galilee region.
[src:arak-drink/arak-drink] Arak is a traditional alcoholic beverage of the Levant and Eastern Mediterranean.
[src:arak-drink/arak-drink] It is distilled and consumed across a wide area in the Middle East, including in Lebanon, Syria, Jordan, Egypt, Iraq, Palestine and Israel.
[src:arak-drink/arak-drink] Sudan, Iran, Morocco, and Greece are also generally recognized as major producers and exporters of Arak.
[src:arak-drink/arak-drink] Arak is a stronger flavored liquor and is usually mixed in proportions of approximately one part arak to two parts water in a traditional Eastern Mediterranean water vessel called an *ibrik* (Arabic: إبريق **ibrīq**), from Middle Persian or Parthian **ābrēz*.
[src:arak-drink/arak-drink] The mixture is then poured into ice-filled cups, usually small, but can also be consumed in regular sized cups.
[src:arak-drink/arak-drink] This dilution causes the clear liquor to turn a translucent milky-white color; this is because anethole, the essential oil of anise, is soluble in alcohol but not in water.
[src:arak-drink/arak-drink] This results in an emulsion whose fine droplets scatter the light and turn the liquid translucent, a phenomenon known as the ouzo effect.
[src:arak-drink/arak-drink] Arak is often served with meze, which may include dozens of small traditional dishes, as well as with grilled meat.
[src:arak-drink/arak-drink] It is also commonly served as an apéritif.
[src:arak-drink/arak-drink] Arak is often called the national drink of Lebanon.
[src:arak-drink/arak-drink] Largely made from the Marawi and Obaideh grape varieties, a center of production is the Bekaa Valley, particularly the Kefraya, Ksara, Domaine des Tourelles, and Massaya vineyards.
[src:arak-drink/arak-drink] Zahlé, where Arak Zahlawi is produced, is considered a capital of arak.
[src:arak-drink/arak-drink] The water used in the production of Arak Zahlawi is traditionally drawn from the Berdawni River.
[src:arak-drink/arak-drink] Before the outbreak of the Syrian Civil War in 2011, production was dominated by two state-run firms, Al-Rayan (based in the city of Sweida) and Al-Mimas (based in a Christian settlement near Homs).
[src:arak-drink/arak-drink] Together, the two companies held about 85% of Syria's market share in arak.
[src:arak-drink/arak-drink] Since the civil war, however, the companies' profits and the price of arak have declined, with their combined market share falling to under half.
[src:arak-drink/arak-drink] Low-quality counterfeits also proliferated, using pure alcohol (rather than fermented grapes) and an aniseed substitute (rather than real aniseed).
[src:arak-drink/arak-drink] Iraq formerly manufactured arak, including in Bashiqa in northern Iraq, but most arak production facilities shut down in the 2010s.
[src:arak-drink/arak-drink] Arak is distilled and consumed by Iraq's Yazidi and Christian minorities, although many members of these groups fled after ISIL seized control of large portions of northern Iraq in 2014.
[src:arak-drink/arak-drink] Amid a rise in Islamic conservatism, the Iraqi parliament passed a ban on the importing, manufacturing, and sale of alcoholic beverages in 2016, prompting protests from Iraqi non-Muslims and rights activists.
[src:arak-drink/arak-drink] The ban was not enforced until it was officially gazetted in 2023, triggering border crackdowns.
[src:arak-drink/arak-drink] The ban is not enforced in Iraq's autonomous Kurdistan Region.
[src:arak-drink/arak-drink] During the age of austerity in the early years of the State of Israel, arak (in Hebrew, ערק) was locally made, with few imports.
[src:arak-drink/arak-drink] The core market for arak was among older, working-class Israelis, and the drink was not favored among younger and modern Israelis.
[src:arak-drink/arak-drink] In the first two decades of the 21st century, however, arak had a resurgence in popularity.
[src:arak-drink/arak-drink] Arak also continues to be popular among Moroccan Jews in Israel, some of whom regard arak as having folk medicine properties.
[src:arak-drink/arak-drink] Israeli tax reforms in 2013 substantially increased the alcohol tax, and this led to consolidation of the arak market.
[src:arak-drink/arak-drink] The most popular producer is Joseph Gold & Sons, a winery established in 1824 in Haifa by the Gold family, which formerly made vodka in Ukraine before establishing an arak distillery in Israel.
[src:arak-drink/arak-drink] The winery, having moved later to Tirat Carmel outside Haifa, produces different arak brands, including Elite Arak, Alouf Arak, and Amir Arak.
[src:arak-drink/arak-drink] Other major arak producers include Barkan Wine Cellars (which produces Arak Ashkelon) and Kawar Distillery (which produces Arak Kawar, Arak Yuda, and Arak Noah).
[src:arak-drink/arak-drink] After the Israeli withdrawal from southern Lebanon in 2000, some former South Lebanon Army members who settled in Israel began to produce arak using Lebanese (Zahlé) methods.
[src:arak-drink/arak-drink] Arak is locally produced by Palestinian Christians.
[src:arak-drink/arak-drink] The West Bank city of Ramallah is a center of arak distillation.
[src:arak-drink/arak-drink] Imports of arak from Palestine to the U.S. increased after imports of Syrian arak were disrupted by the Syrian civil war.
[src:arak-drink/arak-drink] Several arak brands are produced outside of the Eastern Mediterranean.
[src:arak-drink/arak-drink] The Arak Carmel brand is produced in Spain, while the Arak Julenar brand is produced by an Iraqi in Greece.
[src:arak-drink/arak-drink] Arak was once produced in Iran, until it was banned following the 1979 Iranian Revolution.
[src:arak-drink/arak-drink] Iranian Armenians locally manufacture black-market arak in Iran, and some foreign brands are also smuggled in the country.
[src:arak-drink/arak-drink] A locally made Iranian arak moonshine, *aragh sagi*, is made from fermented raisins; in 2020 it sold on the black market for about US$10 for 1.5 liters.
[src:arak-drink/arak-drink] The Persian Empire Distillery, established in 2006 by a Shiraz-born Persian Canadian entrepreneur, distills an arak brand, Arak Saggi, at its distillery in Peterborough, Ontario.
[src:arak-drink/arak-drink] Arak has achieved popularity among consumers in the North Caucasus area of Russia.
[src:arak-drink/arak-drink] Similar aperitifs include the Turkish rakı, the Greek ouzo and tsikoudia, the Italian sambuca and anisette, the Bulgarian and Macedonian mastika, and the Spanish anís.
[src:arak-drink/arak-drink] However, it is unrelated to the similarly named arrack, a sugarcane-based Indonesian liquor.
[src:arak-drink/arak-drink] Manufacturing begins with the vineyards, and quality grapevines are the key to making good arak.
[src:arak-drink/arak-drink] The vines should be very mature and usually of a golden color.
[src:arak-drink/arak-drink] Instead of being irrigated, the vineyards are left to the care of the Mediterranean climate and make use of the natural rain and sun.
[src:arak-drink/arak-drink] The grapes, which are harvested in late September and early October, are crushed and put in barrels together with the juice (in Arabic *el romeli*) and left to ferment for three weeks.
[src:arak-drink/arak-drink] Occasionally the whole mix is stirred to release the CO2.
[src:arak-drink/arak-drink] Both pot stills and column stills are used.
[src:arak-drink/arak-drink] Stills are usually made of stainless steel or copper.
[src:arak-drink/arak-drink] Copper stills with a Moorish shape are the most sought after.
[src:arak-drink/arak-drink] The alcohol collected in the first distillation undergoes a second distillation, but this time it is mixed with aniseed.
[src:arak-drink/arak-drink] The ratio of alcohol to aniseed may vary and it is one of the major factors in the quality of the final product.
[src:arak-drink/arak-drink] The finished product is produced during a final distillation which takes place at the lowest possible temperature.
[src:arak-drink/arak-drink] For a quality arak, the finished spirit is then aged in clay amphoras to allow the angels' share to evaporate.
[src:arak-drink/arak-drink] The liquid remaining after this step is the most suitable for consumption.
